itle> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=spaceguy3>SpaceGuy3</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/30/03 9:41 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=935.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/16.gif" align=absmiddle>  Lets Go To Mars</span><hr size=1> Ok, lets stop talking and lets go to Mars.  Here is my proposal using as much off the shelf technology as possible:<br>
<br>
Send a mix of 3 astronauts/cosmonauts, maybe 1 Russian, 1 American, 1 Chinese.<br>
<br>
Use a Mir Core type module as the habitat module for the journey to Mars and back.  Launch requirement - 1 Proton Launch into LEO.  A Progress Launch carrying outfitting necessary to bring the Mir Core module to operational status is probably needed, along with a manned Soyuz Launch in LEO to unload the Progress and outfit the module for operational use.  This Soyuz flight would probably spend a week or two in LEO outfitting the Module, and then return to earth in their Soyuz.  The Progress would offload its additional fuel, and then undock and commanded into a destructive reentry.<br>
<br>
Launch 4 progress resupply vessels using Soyuz launchers to dock with the Mir Core module in LEO with supplies for the journey.  This should provide 16 tons of supplies along with storage space for trash on the journey.  Launch requirement - 4 Soyuz launches with Progress vehicles loaded out to the max with supplies - food, water, fuel, supplies.  I envision these docked around the outer docking hub ring, similar to the way modules extended from Mir.  The Progress solar panels would also provide electricity and redundancy for propulsion needs for course corrections, etc.<br>
<br>
Launch the Mars Landing/surface return vehicle and dock to the Mir Core module in LEO.  Launch requirement - 1 Proton launch with landing/return vehicle.  The landing and return vehicle would have to be developed as new technology, however, off the shelf technology could be used to build such a craft.  KISS - Keep it simple, stupid.  Keep the design of the landing and return vehicle simple, for reliability and safety.<br>
<br>
Launch the Mars injection stage into LEO to dock with the Mir Core configuration and Progress vehicles.  I envision this stage docking to the aft end of the Mir core module.  This would require 1 Proton launch.  This stage would be used to insert the configuration of the core, Progress vehicles and Landing/return craft into a cruise to Mars.<br>
<br>
Launch a crew of 3 on a Soyuz spacecraft to the core module, and then off to Mars.<br>
<br>
The Mars orbital insertion burn would be completed by one or more of the Progress vehicles docked to the Mir Core Module.<br>
<br>
The landing craft would descend with 2 crew-members, 1 would stay behind to tend the core module in Mars Orbit.<br>
<br>
Before the return home burn, in Mars orbit, 2 of the Progress vechicles would be emptied, their excess fuel offloaded to the Core Module, and they would be undocked from the core module, decreasing return home mass.<br>
<br>
The return to Earth burn would be completed by a combination of the other Progress vehicles docked to the Module.<br>
<br>
The Earth insertion burn would be completed by a combination of the Progress vehicles with remaining fuel, and the fuel remaining in the Mir Core module propulsion unit for a highly eliptical insertion orbit around earth.<br>
<br>
The crew would use the Soyuz they launched to the module 2 years earlier to undock and return to earth in.<br>
<br>
This is my proposal for a journey to Mars and back using existing technology AND hardware for the most part.<br>
<br>
Launches needed:<br>
<br>
7 Proton  Approx $100 million each<br>
2 manned Soyuz launches - 1 to outfit, 1 for the Mars Crew - $30 million each<br>
5 unmanned Soyuz launches - 5 Progress Resupply Ships - $30 million each.<br>
<br>
New flight Hardware development costs - proabably $1 to $2 billion.<br>
<br>
Mir Core Module Cost:  $250 million<br>
<br>
Total costs - $2 to $3.5 billion.  <br>
<br>
Thats doable, lets stop talking and lets go.  We can go to Mars cheaper than we can build the ISS.<br>
